The Resurgence of the Great Leader
London — — The Battle of Waterloo has been two hundred years ago, and Napoleon's disastrous defeat in that battle severely damaged France's self-respect, to the point that General de Gaulle omitted mentioning the battle altogether when writing the history of the French army.
Nevertheless, if you accept that "greatness" is some kind of personal trait, then both Napoleon and de Gaulle can be considered among the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as "great leaders."
In Marx's view, the class struggle in France created the environment in which a "strange mediocrity" like Napoleon could become a hero.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not particularly outstanding as a general, and his victories should be credited to the courage and devotion of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
Whether Napoleon was great or not, we must clarify whether any leader can be described as great.
If the answer is yes, then who exactly can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believes that great leaders must meet two particularly important criteria.
First, can this leader recognize historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck did, as did his German contemporary Konrad Adenauer; borrowing Bismarck's memorable phrase, both heard the "sound of God's cloak."
Secondly, did this leader make important decisions?
Of course, if a leader is forced to make a decision, he or she cannot be blamed for it, nor can they claim credit for it.
Therefore, the key is whether the leader had the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the right decision on behalf of the nation.
De Gaulle should therefore be ranked among the greatest leaders without a doubt.
He almost single-handedly brought France out of the post-war decline.
After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country, suppressing two failed coups, ending the Algerian War, and drafting the Constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview, establishing their place in the post-war global order.
In fact, the ultimate impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in shaping their nations' worldviews was somewhat excessive.
Their successors continued to view the world—and France's role in it—through the lens of constrained rationality and distorted decision-making for years to come.
The leaders of both countries after them were never able to achieve accomplishments that could match those of the two great leaders.
But there was one British prime minister who could match them: Margaret Thatcher, a highly controversial figure, loved by as many as those who hated her.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was the result of resistance from her own cabinet and party.
But it does not take approval from everyone to be a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics could not deny her influence.
As well as being the first female prime minister of the United Kingdom and almost certainly the earliest female prime minister of other countries in the world, Thatcher helped reverse Britain's economic decline.
Moreover, her attack on overly powerful trade unions enhanced the nation's manageability at a time when it seemed to be sliding into chaos and disorder.
Given this, she undoubtedly has a claim to be a "great leader."
Similarly, although far from flawless, Deng Xiaoping also qualifies as a great leader.
Aside from assisting Mao Zedong in wrongdoing, Deng played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre.
But Deng also revitalized the market, leading China onto an unprecedented path of development and prosperity that ultimately lifted hundreds of millions of Chinese out of poverty.
Many people consider Singapore's founder and long-serving prime minister Lee Kuan Yew to be very great, although he might have wished to showcase his talents on a bigger stage.
In fact, the size of a country does not seem to affect a person's ability to become a great leader.
I said that a country as small as Luxembourg is unlikely to produce a great leader not out of any disrespect, especially since the country's political atmosphere is generally not highly controversial.
The United States, being vast, is sufficient as a cradle for the birth of great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — though not intellectual giants — demonstrated extraordinary judgment in establishing a postwar international order that sustained world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possessed exceptional talent — namely, the art of inspiring and persuading.
John F. Kennedy was a man of many talents.
He accomplished a great task: defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His inspirational talent was unparalleled; in fact, his assassination after his death solidified the tradition he left behind.
In South Africa, no one has yet been considered a great figure after Mandela, the former president, who embodied courage, authority, and graceful magnanimity.
In fact, he was the most charming and appealing leader I have ever seen; the other two — former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former U.S. Secretary of State Colin Powell — were either Africans or African Americans.
So what about today?
The only one qualified to claim greatness is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at the beginning but made few mistakes when making important decisions.
Kohl established generous terms for German unification; Merkel stood up to Putin during his invasion of Ukraine and took a tolerant approach to the immigration crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy were wrong.
Political leaders — the exercisers of political power — can change the situation, for better or worse.
Merkel is the most obvious example today, as she provided direction for Europe in dealing with high-stakes survival crises.
